#BLACKCATPRIDE - FPS Social Media Spotlight

This spotlight is a week early to recognize 9/11. Fredericktown Alternative Learning Campus (FALC) spent this week remembering the events that took place on September 11, 2001. The 4th, 5th, and 6th grade teachers took their students on a memory walk throughout the week incorporating a variety of activities that provided the students with opportunities to learn and connect with this time in our history that must never be forgotten. Please keep an eye out for the Democrat News “Blackcat Spotlight” during the week of 9/21/20 for a complete overview of how FALC teachers and students remember 9/11! *Pics attached #alwayremember #weareblackcats

post_text:
#BLACKCATPRIDE - FPS Social Media Spotlight

Fredericktown Elementary "Students of the Month" enjoyed a picnic lunch with Principal Clauser and 3 of the FPS School Resource Officers on Friday, September 11. Each classroom teacher chose a student from their room that has been demonstrating the school’s character word of the month- KIND. The 20 character students received a special invitation to take part in the picnic lunch, which was donated by Domino’s Pizza in Fredericktown. The students practiced safe social distancing while enjoying the beautiful weather and social time with the principal. Please keep an eye out for more information of this special event in the Blackcat Spotlight of the Democrat News! #FESbuildingcharacter #kindnessmatters #weareblackcats

DATE: 9/8/20
ATTN: Fredericktown R-1 Families

This week the USDA released an update extending the summer meal waiver through Dec. 31, 2020, or until funding to operate the program runs out. As a result of this extension, all virtual and in-person students will receive FREE breakfast and lunch starting today and continuing through the time period stated above. If this service is discontinued prior to December 31st, due to exhausted federal funds for the program, we will communicate with our Fredericktown R-1 families. Thank you

Tonight we celebrated some very special and dedicated educators. We were unable to honor them at the end of the year due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Our 2019-20 retiring educators were honored with gifts, a special plaque, and some yummy refreshments! We wish each retiree a very blessed and relaxing retirement. We are so very thankful for your dedication to our staff, students, and community!

2019- 20 Retiring Staff Members:
Tuck Boston, Eric Boushie, Bill Clauser, Pam Helm, Terri Jenkins, Crystal Miller, James Miller, Bob Moore, Brett Reutzel, Polly Reutzel, Sonya Starkey, Brenda Tilk, and Sally Wood

post_text:
Fredericktown R-1 Parents and Community-

As a follow-up to the information sent out earlier, we wanted to release some newly provided information. In cooperation with Madison Co. Health Dept., we were contacted and informed that there are no identified close contacts at this time for either positive case reported today. The CDC defines close contact as any individual who was within 6 feet of an infected person for at least 15 minutes. As always, we will continue to keep you informed and practice mitigation on all campuses and buses during the COVID-19 pandemic. Thank you.

Parents as Teachers Survey- OPTIONAL

https://www.votervoice.net/BroadcastLinks/R_O-dgHuLlY2bmbkVDw9Fg

Kids Win Missouri, a statewide child well-being advocacy organization, is working to understand what the ideal early childhood system is for Missouri's children, families, and providers. They have developed this short survey (about 5 minutes to complete) to understand the dreams, hopes, challenges, and barriers of the early childhood system. This survey will inform and help Kids Win Missouri prioritize its early childhood work and partnership. They are giving away 3 $100 Amazon gift cards at random by the end of August as the survey is wrapped up. Questions regarding the survey can be sent to Craig Stevenson at cstevenson@kidswinmissouri.org

The survey will be available until August 31, 2020. Any families or providers that may be interested in sharing their experience with early childhood services, feel free to complete the survey.

I hope you will take 5 minutes to complete the survey!

post_text:
Summer School

We will be sending out surveys the week of May 11th about a possible summer school. The surveys will be sent out through building Remind 101s and other social media. We hope to have a regular face to face summer school. A summer school session could be held later in the summer than normal (possibly late July or early August). The survey will address interest for multiple options of format. Please take your time completing the survey and thinking about these options. Your input will greatly influence how we construct our summer school session.

post_text:
Message from a wonderful group of parents and grandparents. We plan to hang the banners on the fence by the football field facing the highway:

Debbie Wojtczuk has spoke to someone in Marble Hill that will do a Senior banner 12” X 18” for $16.18 each. This includes the pole to put them on. We would like to make sure every senior has one, and we’re trying to get it approved to put them at the school. You can choose the picture.
The email to send picture is serenityhouseflowers@yahoo.com. Add to your email that it is for Fredericktown. She will let you see it and approve it before she makes it.
She will then send a Paypal link to you for payment.
Let me know once this is done, so I can mark you off our list.
Please share!!

post_text: The census also helps with funding for public education.
shared_text:
University of Missouri Extension Madison County
April 13 at 7:42 AM ·

Madison County's self-response rate on the 2020 Census is only 39.7% at this time. Our county and state response rate will determine how much funding we receive for important things like highway planning and construction, our Head Start programs, and housing assistance for older adults (among many others)!

If you have not taken the time to respond, please do so at https://2020census.gov/. It will only take about 10 minutes and it has the potential to have a major impact in our county and our state!

#ExtendMU #BusComEx #MUExtSER MU Extension in the Southeast Region

April 9 at 3:12 PM ·

Missouri Governor Mike Parson announced in the Thursday, April 9 press briefing that Missouri schools will remain closed through this school year. DESE, along with several school superintendents from across the state, made the recommendation to Governor Mike Parson on April 9. Learn more about this announcement here in remarks by Commissioner of Education Margie Vandeven.

Shanna Sorg‎Madison County Food Helpers
April 4 at 11:21 PM ·

A dear friend called this afternoon to check in on me and to let me know she had stopped off at one of the Community Sharing Boxes and filled the cabinet with some food. She then went to Wal-Mart to get a few necessities and also purchased some more items for the next time she could donate again to the Community Sharing Box. Those additional items didn't quite make it back home with her because when she was driving home from Wal-Mart she noticed that the box she had just filled 30 minutes prior was already empty. Just wanted to remind everyone of the 2 Community Sharing Boxes in town (located at the Methodist Church on S. Main and at the Catholic church on W. Main) and that anyone can drop off at those boxes at anytime. Thank you!

Thursday's delivery will be delayed due to bus inspections. We will post on Facebook when deliveries are on their way for Thursday.

Catpack Program Announcement:
The Fredericktown R-1 School District is currently providing 77 students weekly with a weekend supply of food through our Catpack program. Tomorrow those 77 students will bring home a bag of food that they would have been provided on Friday, March 20. Beginning on Friday, March 27, the Catpacks will be available for pick up at the Middle School during breakfast pickups (7:30-8:30) or lunch pickups (Noon to 1:00). If the family is receiving lunch deliveries on Fridays, the Catpack will be delivered with the students' lunch.

If you are interested in donating to this program, please contact the Middle School.

Deep cough
Gastrointestinal Symptoms
Fever greater than 100.4 degrees

post_text:
As we are thick in the middle of flu season, a few reminders from the CDC:

Families, students, and school staff can keep from getting viral infections in three ways:

Practicing good hand hygiene. Students and staff members should wash their hands often with soap and water, especially after coughing or sneezing. Alcohol based hand rubs are also useful.

Practicing respiratory etiquette. The main way that a virus such as the flu spreads from person to person in the droplets produced by coughs and sneezes, so it’s important to cover your mouth and nose with a tissue when you cough or sneeze. If you don’t have a tissue, cough or sneeze into your elbow or shoulder, not into your hands.

Staying home if you’re sick. Keeping sick students at home means that they keep their viruses to themselves rather than sharing them with others. Students, staff, and their families must take personal responsibility for helping to slow the spread of the virus by practicing these steps to keep from getting sick and protecting others from getting sick.

Our Learning Zone Financial Classes continue next Tuesday, February 25th:

Credit plays a vital role in our day to day lives. Many of us don’t realize the weight that our credit holds when it comes to making financial decisions. Join us on February 25th as we discuss credit scores, credit reports and what it takes to build or rebuild your credit. This class is for everyone, whether you have no credit, good credit, bad credit or downright ugly credit, you will be able to walk away from our conversation with a better understanding of how to make your credit work for you.

post_text: This is great stuff. Thank you Mrs. Harris for posting this moment.
shared_text:
Katie Harris
February 19 at 12:34 AM ·

Tonight was West County high schools last basketball game of the season, and hands down the best. Not because we won, because we actually lost. Its because of a young man named Tyler, #10 who has disabilities and actually plays on a special olympics type team locally, and is also the manager for WC. Layne often takes Tyler home after practices, and picks him up so that he can attend practices on days they don’t have school, but still have basketball.
Tyler comes over to our house to hang out with Caleb, they talk wrestling and superheroes, and who knows what else! Tyler is an awesome kid that hasn’t been dealt the best hand in life, but you would never be able to tell by talking to him.

I have never became teary eyed at any game, until tonight. This video shows the love that our coaches have for our boys. And the sportsman ship shown by Fredericktown, when one of their teammates handed the ball over to Tyler was simply amazing. What a great end to a season, and the smile on Tyler’s face after the game tells me that he will never forget this night!

Kelly A. Burlison Middle School
January 11 at 9:29 PM ·

KABMS Robocats participated in their FIRST ever robotics meet in Farmington at St. Joseph’s Catholic School. The Robocats competed against robotics teams that were more established, experienced, and ranked the best in the state and nation. We were the only team with no practice field and placed 10th out of 24 teams in the SKILLS category and 16th out of 24 in the TEAMS category!

Last, but certainly not least, KABMS received the SPORTSMANSHIP AWARD! They said we were constantly offering to help, praising other teams, and consistently a positive and supportive team to others even though it was our first match. Mrs. Mills is the sponsor who assisted the students today during competition! CONGRATULATIONS Robocats and Mrs. Mills on your first meet! I have a feeling this is just the beginning of many more!

Are you an employer of food, agriculture or forestry workers in Missouri? If so, we need your input! By taking our short survey or participating in a focus group, your anonymous input will be utilized in creating a workforce needs assessment of Missouri’s food, agriculture, and forestry industries. This assessment will guide future initiatives to strengthen and grow your industry’s workforce. To take our survey or to sign up for a focus group, visit http://bit.ly/MOAgEmployers.

This initiative is a partnership of University of Missouri Extension, Missouri Department of Agriculture, & Missouri Agricultural Foundation. For more information, contact Dr. Mark White, with Missouri Extension’s Labor and Workforce Development program, whitemc@missouri.edu.
